body:
This *might* be related to what I just tracked down while working out kinks with new hardware.

With the number of supported modifiers on formats growing, (11 on all relevant formats for me at the time of writing), we actually out-grow the 2048-byte buffer we were using to construct the SPA version of the format params. This *seems* a bit excessive, but I don't know how the internals of `spa_pod_builder` work, so once I confirmed this I didn't look too much farther to see if we're leaking something temporarily there.

This results in the "changes" we think we're making to the relevant formats (removal of incompatible modifier) not taking effect, so we push either identical, or null changes through to pipewire, which realizes there's no change, and never triggers a change event on either end.

It wouldn't be a bad idea to add some defensive coding to prevent the "trying the same params twice" case to prevent an actual logic issue in the future, but in the immediate time frame, simply increasing the buffer size from 2048->4096 resolves it (at least with my hardware). IMO, these buffers should either be dynamically resizable or *far* larger than that to cover future use cases like more metadata. While there's a time for the assumption around a max buffer size, this negotiation is hopefully seldom. I'm not yet any kind of decent at SPA, so I didn't take a crack at it yet, but I can :)

If you want an easy way to confirm this overflow, just break at the end of `build_format_params`, and if any element of `params` is NULL that doesn't correspond to a `format_type` that has already exhausted its list of qualifiers, then the builder has overflowed.

I'm not familiar with what the *expected* behavior of passing `NULL` values to `pw_stream_update_params` within the `[0,n_params)` range is either, so regardless of the infinite loop this wasn't likely terrific behavior :rofl: 

